pr_title: WIP: Abstract type for summary statistics (Mean)
pr_body:
Resolves #275, #184, #274 
Partial implementation of @smishr's confidence interval function
Implemented Mean structure as an abstract SummaryStat 

**Remaining to do on this PR :**
- [ ] Implement "t" and "margin" confidence intervals
- [ ] Add more attributes to Mean structure (standard error of estimate, ...)
- [ ] Add support for ReplicateDesign
- [ ] Write test/SummaryStats.jl
- [ ] Make sure documentation is in order
- [ ] Delete mean.jl once all functionality is implemented in Mean struct ?

Can implement Total, Quantile, and Ratio later
pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 1124248937, 'comment_body': 'Yes this abstract type looks good', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 3, 3, 10, 1, 2, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'smishr', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1124251419, 'comment_body': 'EDIT: After reviewing I think you can just copy the entire of `_ci` from 190 and rename it here.
- I think `estimate` and `std_dev` should be type `AbstractVector` (like in `_ci` in #190 ). This way you can pass whole column of estimates at the same time.
- I would keep `confint` in a different file `confint.jl`.
', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 3, 3, 10, 3, 35, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'smishr', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1124258305, 'comment_body': '- This should be an addition to the existing `mean.jl` file. You can add with multiple dispatch you can define `mean(x::Symbol, design::ReplicateDesign, ci_type=`normal` ...)` see #190 line 169-170 of what the defintion of function can be
- build for `ReplicateDesign` first, since `SurveyDesign` doesnt have std error yet', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 3, 3, 10, 10, 24, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'smishr', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1124260299, 'comment_body': 'Am wondering if `SummaryStats` should be an `AbstractFunction` instead?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 3, 3, 10, 12, 35, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'smishr', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1124260909, 'comment_body': '- This should be done as part of edits inside `mean.jl`
- Im not sure whether the struct would just need two things x and design
- I have gut feeling that `Mean` should be a Function, not a struct. Lets ask @ayushpatnaikgit this. ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 3, 3, 10, 13, 14, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'smishr', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1124944515, 'comment_body': 'I went with the idea that it's easier to have all summary statistics as a struct in a single file (`SummaryStats.jl`) since it's easier to manage, if we want to add another statistic later on you would just add it to this one file. 

The reason for having `Mean` as a struct (as well as a Function) is the same : if we want to add other statistics, and we want all statistics to have a set of basic elements (e.g. an estimate), you would write this into `SummaryStats` which is the "parent abstract type" and it would be automatically passed down to all the other statistics (since `Mean <: SummaryStats`). At least this is my understanding.

Also `mean.jl` (and quantile, ratio, total) has a lot of dispatched functions, so I thought it'd be more efficient and maintainable to have only 1 file which implements all summary stats, instead of 1 file per stat (`mean.jl`, `quantile.jl` etc) which has multiple dispatched functions inside.

I agree with having `confint.jl` separately though.

Thoughts ?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 3, 3, 19, 52, 33, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'nadiaenh', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1124945689, 'comment_body': '- to your first point : see my reply to your comment on line 60
- to your 2nd point : yes that makes sense ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 3, 3, 19, 53, 53, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'nadiaenh', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1124946811, 'comment_body': "Didn't know about this, will look into it !", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 3, 3, 19, 55, 9, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'nadiaenh', 'type': 'User'}]

pr_title: Add GLM with design-based standard errors
pr_body:
Building on Ayush's code for GLM: 
- [x] renamed `glm( )` to `svyglm( )` to avoid ambiguity and be consistent with R naming
- [x] changed variable names and added comment for clarity
- [x] added test for GLM's in `bsrs`
- [x] added documentation for GLM's 
- [x] improved docstring
- [x] use Survey.variance( ) to calculate SE's after closing #297 

**Ready to be merged as of August 24, 2023**

pr_title: New data structures to support multiple replicate methods.
pr_body:
This PR introduces a "replicate type" for every `ReplicateDesign` object. The purpose is mainly to help with multiple dispatch on difference replicate methods.

We have introduced a new abstract type called `InferenceMethod`, which will be a supertype for all inference types. For now, the package only supports two inference methods, which we've encoded by the `BootstrapReplicates` and `JackknifeReplicates` structs.

Relevant changes have been made to the `ReplicateDesign` struct to incorporate the new structure.

Also, the `mean`, `total` and `quantile` functions have now been written using the generic `variance` function. Since `ratio` takes two columns as it's arguments, it can't be implemented using `variance` as of now (see #295 ).

Closes #261

pr_title: Add GLM with design-based standard errors
pr_body:
Building on Ayush's code for GLM: 
- [x] renamed `glm( )` to `svyglm( )` to avoid ambiguity and be consistent with R naming
- [x] changed variable names and added comment for clarity
- [x] added test for GLM's in `bsrs`
- [x] added documentation for GLM's 
- [x] improved docstring
- [x] use Survey.variance( ) to calculate SE's after closing #297 

**Ready to be merged as of August 24, 2023**

pr_title: WIP: Abstract type for summary statistics (Mean)
pr_body:
Resolves #275, #184, #274 
Partial implementation of @smishr's confidence interval function
Implemented Mean structure as an abstract SummaryStat 

**Remaining to do on this PR :**
- [ ] Implement "t" and "margin" confidence intervals
- [ ] Add more attributes to Mean structure (standard error of estimate, ...)
- [ ] Add support for ReplicateDesign
- [ ] Write test/SummaryStats.jl
- [ ] Make sure documentation is in order
- [ ] Delete mean.jl once all functionality is implemented in Mean struct ?

Can implement Total, Quantile, and Ratio later
pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 1124248937, 'comment_body': 'Yes this abstract type looks good', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 3, 3, 10, 1, 2, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'smishr', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1124251419, 'comment_body': 'EDIT: After reviewing I think you can just copy the entire of `_ci` from 190 and rename it here.
- I think `estimate` and `std_dev` should be type `AbstractVector` (like in `_ci` in #190 ). This way you can pass whole column of estimates at the same time.
- I would keep `confint` in a different file `confint.jl`.
', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 3, 3, 10, 3, 35, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'smishr', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1124258305, 'comment_body': '- This should be an addition to the existing `mean.jl` file. You can add with multiple dispatch you can define `mean(x::Symbol, design::ReplicateDesign, ci_type=`normal` ...)` see #190 line 169-170 of what the defintion of function can be
- build for `ReplicateDesign` first, since `SurveyDesign` doesnt have std error yet', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 3, 3, 10, 10, 24, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'smishr', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1124260299, 'comment_body': 'Am wondering if `SummaryStats` should be an `AbstractFunction` instead?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 3, 3, 10, 12, 35, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'smishr', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1124260909, 'comment_body': '- This should be done as part of edits inside `mean.jl`
- Im not sure whether the struct would just need two things x and design
- I have gut feeling that `Mean` should be a Function, not a struct. Lets ask @ayushpatnaikgit this. ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 3, 3, 10, 13, 14, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'smishr', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1124944515, 'comment_body': 'I went with the idea that it's easier to have all summary statistics as a struct in a single file (`SummaryStats.jl`) since it's easier to manage, if we want to add another statistic later on you would just add it to this one file. 

The reason for having `Mean` as a struct (as well as a Function) is the same : if we want to add other statistics, and we want all statistics to have a set of basic elements (e.g. an estimate), you would write this into `SummaryStats` which is the "parent abstract type" and it would be automatically passed down to all the other statistics (since `Mean <: SummaryStats`). At least this is my understanding.

Also `mean.jl` (and quantile, ratio, total) has a lot of dispatched functions, so I thought it'd be more efficient and maintainable to have only 1 file which implements all summary stats, instead of 1 file per stat (`mean.jl`, `quantile.jl` etc) which has multiple dispatched functions inside.

I agree with having `confint.jl` separately though.

Thoughts ?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 3, 3, 19, 52, 33, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'nadiaenh', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1124945689, 'comment_body': '- to your first point : see my reply to your comment on line 60
- to your 2nd point : yes that makes sense ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 3, 3, 19, 53, 53, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'nadiaenh', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1124946811, 'comment_body': "Didn't know about this, will look into it !", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 3, 3, 19, 55, 9, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'nadiaenh', 'type': 'User'}]

pr_body:
- Add documentation for Jackknife survey design
- Add support for design-based variance for bootstrap and jackknife replicate designs
- Update `bydomain` to use with statistical summary functions
- Update `mean`, `quantile`, `total`, and `ratio` to use with `bydomain`
- Renamed `variance` to `stderr`

Closes #295 and #301

pr_title: Add GLM with design-based standard errors
pr_body:
Building on Ayush's code for GLM: 
- [x] renamed `glm( )` to `svyglm( )` to avoid ambiguity and be consistent with R naming
- [x] changed variable names and added comment for clarity
- [x] added test for GLM's in `bsrs`
- [x] added documentation for GLM's 
- [x] improved docstring
- [x] use Survey.variance( ) to calculate SE's after closing #297 

**Ready to be merged as of August 24, 2023**

pr_title: Add GLM with design-based standard errors
pr_body:
Building on Ayush's code for GLM: 
- [x] renamed `glm( )` to `svyglm( )` to avoid ambiguity and be consistent with R naming
- [x] changed variable names and added comment for clarity
- [x] added test for GLM's in `bsrs`
- [x] added documentation for GLM's 
- [x] improved docstring
- [x] use Survey.variance( ) to calculate SE's after closing #297 

**Ready to be merged as of August 24, 2023**
